# =============================================================================
# Civil Rights Act of 1964 — July 2, 1964
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ev_cra64_trigger
title: July 2, 1964
on-arrival: lbj_ev_cra64 = 1; lbj_cr_progress += 2; lbj_dixiecrats -= 14; lbj_liberals += 10; lbj_south_backlash += 14; lbj_racial_tension -= 10; lbj_credibility += 6; lbj_unity += 4; lbj_capital -= 10; lbj_jfk_shadow -= 8
new-page: true

The Civil Rights Act of 1964 passes the Senate 73 to 27 after a seventy-four day filibuster — the longest in Senate history.

You sign it in the East Room. Television cameras. Five hundred guests. The pens go to the people who made it possible: King, Roy Wilkins, Whitney Young, John Lewis. You hand them out one by one.

Russell watches the signing on television in his office. He does not attend.

When the room clears you tell an aide — you will say this to several people over the years and it will get back to the press eventually — *"We have lost the South for a generation."*

You mean the Democratic Party. You are not sure a generation is long enough.

The Act prohibits discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin. It covers employment, public accommodations, federally assisted programs. It is the most significant civil rights legislation since Reconstruction.

It is not enough. You know it is not enough. The movement knows it. Tomorrow the work continues.

