# =============================================================================
# The 1964 Election — November 3, 1964
# The landslide. The window opening.
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ev_election64_trigger
title: November 3, 1964
on-arrival: lbj_ev_election64 = 1; lbj_approval += 12; lbj_capital += 25; lbj_liberals += 8; lbj_labor += 6; lbj_unity += 8; lbj_jfk_shadow -= 15; lbj_continuity -= 4; lbj_far_right -= 5
new-page: true

61.1 percent of the popular vote.

Four hundred eighty-six electoral votes to fifty-two. You carry forty-four states. Goldwater carries his home state of Arizona and five states in the Deep South — states you knew you were going to lose, states you lost the moment you signed the Civil Rights Act, states you would lose again.

The 89th Congress: sixty-eight Democratic senators, two hundred ninety-five Democratic representatives. The largest majority since Roosevelt's first term. The window is open. You have known since November 22nd, 1963 that windows close. You are going to move as fast as the institution allows.

Lady Bird watches the returns with you. At some point after midnight she says: *"It's yours now, Lyndon. Really yours."*

She means the presidency. She also means something else — that the question of legitimacy, of whether you were the real thing or a placeholder for a dead man, has been answered by sixty-one percent of the American people.

You feel it. For one night you feel it completely.

Tomorrow the work begins.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

# =============================================================================
# Medicare — July 30, 1965
# Independence, Missouri. In front of Harry Truman.
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ev_medicare_trigger
title: Independence, Missouri
on-arrival: lbj_ev_medicare = 1; lbj_gs_progress += 2; lbj_approval += 5; lbj_liberals += 8; lbj_labor += 6; lbj_poverty -= 10; lbj_capital -= 12; lbj_far_right += 5; lbj_dixiecrats -= 4
new-page: true

You fly to Independence, Missouri.

Harry S. Truman is eighty-one years old. He proposed national health insurance in 1949. The American Medical Association called it socialized medicine and killed it. He has been waiting sixteen years.

You sign the Medicare and Medicaid Act in the Truman Library with the thirty-third President of the United States sitting beside you. You hand him the first two Medicare cards — card number one for him, card number two for Bess.

He cries. You are not going to mention that part, but he does.

Eighteen million Americans over sixty-five will be covered in the first year. Medicaid will cover the poor regardless of age. The numbers will grow every year until the program is as permanent as the government itself — until people receive it the way they receive the weather, as simply a feature of the world.

The AMA called it socialized medicine. You call it done.

