@lbj_ev_vra65_scene
title: The Voting Rights Act
new-page: true

The Voting Rights Act passes the Senate 77 to 19.

You sign it in the President's Room of the Capitol — the same room where Lincoln signed a bill freeing slaves pressed into Confederate service — with Martin Luther King in the room, with John Lewis in the room, with the leadership of the movement watching.

The Act prohibits discriminatory voting practices. It provides for federal oversight of elections in states with a history of discrimination. It will add nearly a million Black voters to the rolls in the South within a year.

Five days ago, you addressed a joint session of Congress and said *we shall overcome.* Tonight the words are law.

Russell is not in the room.

